<html>
<head>
  <title>JavaScript Debugger Aid</title>
  <script type="text/javascript" src="../src/dojo/dojo.js" djConfig="parseOnLoad: true"></script>

  <!-- Load JavaScript files via Script statements for better debugging information than Dojo's eval. -->
  <script type="text/javascript" src="../src/anzo/client/JMSNotificationService.js"></script>

</head>
<body>
<h3>JavaScript Debugger Aid</h3>

<p>
This file is useful when syntax errors appear in JavaScript code being loaded by the Dojo module system.
When code is loaded by the Dojo module system it looses line number information in the syntax errors.
</p>

To use:
<ol>
    <li>Edit this HTML document to add the potentially problematic file in a &lt;script&gt; tag. See the examples already there.</li>
    <li>Load this document in the browser you'll get a better script error message sent by the browser.</li>
</ol>

<p>
Once of the most common errors is to have trailing commas in object or array literals (ex. <code>{ foo: 1, bar: 2, }</code>
or <code>[ 1, 2, ]</code>). Internet Explorer considers that a script error while Firefox and Rhino are more forgiving.
</p>
</body>
</html>
